    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zflGZ.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 440158,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 829571,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/829571/assylias",
                "reputation": 330070,
                "display_name": "assylias",
                "accept_rate": 94
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1389983711,
            "creation_date": 1389982619,
            "body": "<p>One solution is using a private holder class:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class SomeClass {\n    private static class ResourceHolder {\n        private static final Resource INSTANCE = new Resource();\n    }\n\n    public static Resource getInstance() { \n        return ResourceHolder.INSTANCE;\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>the instance will be initialized when <code>SomeClass.getInstance()<\/code> is called the first time.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 21193002,
            "question_id": 21192950,
            "last_edit_date": 1389983711
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/1pvWd.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 3152821,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2665890,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2665890/obicere",
                "reputation": 3019,
                "display_name": "Obicere",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1389982856,
            "creation_date": 1389982856,
            "body": "<p>Another way you could do this is use static initialization:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class SomeClass {\n\n    private static final Object[] CONTENT;\n\n    static {\n        CONTENT = new Object[SomeOtherClass.getContentSize()]; // To show you can access runtime variables\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will initialize the <code>CONTENT<\/code> array once the class is loaded using the ClassLoader.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 21193074,
            "question_id": 21192950
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53ee9941b3fefef67175daf212e62d41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 23121,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 57695,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/57695/peter-lawrey",
                "reputation": 535107,
                "display_name": "Peter Lawrey",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1389985016,
            "creation_date": 1389985016,
            "body": "<p>The simplest lazy initialisation is to use an <code>enum<\/code> with one instance.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>enum Singleton {\n    INSTANCE; // lazy initialised\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The added problem is you want initialisation values.  To handle this you can nest the class.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>enum Utility {;\n     static MyType val;\n     static OtherType val2;\n\n     enum Holder {\n         INSTANCE;\n\n         Holder() {\n            // uses val and val2\n         }\n     }\n\n     public static Holder getInstance(MyType val, OtherType val2) {\n         Utility.val = val;\n         Utility.val2 = val2;\n         return Holder.INSTANCE; // only created the first time.\n     }\n }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note: this is thread safe as static block initialisation is safe.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 21193700,
            "question_id": 21192950
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/15JSR.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 5539,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 8969,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8969/tom",
                "reputation": 45121,
                "display_name": "Tom",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1389982889,
            "creation_date": 1389982889,
            "body": "<p>Something like:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static abstract class Lazy&lt;T&gt; {\n\n    private T t = null;\n\n    public synchronized T get() {\n        if (t == null) {\n            t = create();\n        }\n        return t;\n    }\n\n    protected abstract T create();\n}\n\npublic static final Lazy&lt;List&lt;String&gt;&gt; lazyList = new Lazy&lt;List&lt;String&gt;&gt;(){\n\n    @Override\n    protected List&lt;String&gt; create() {\n        return new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n    }\n}; \n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 21193081,
            "question_id": 21192950
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f0aa6977c75f54ca9033d4f4d0244023?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 39409,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 113632,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/113632/dimo414",
                "reputation": 49322,
                "display_name": "dimo414",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1389983918,
            "creation_date": 1389983460,
            "body": "<p>I'll caution you up front, what you're describing has a bit of code smell, and I suspect you'll do better to avoid this pattern entirely.  A static resource that depends on external runtime state breaks all sorts of best practices about variable scope.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>What you're describing, however, would best be implemented by either a <a href=\"http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/base/Supplier.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Supplier<\/code><\/a> or a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/Future.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Future<\/code><\/a>, depending on the work involved in successfully constructing the object you need.  The difference is somewhat pedantic, but you'd generally use a <code>Future<\/code> to hold a reference that will take a long time to compute, while a <code>Supplier<\/code> generally returns quickly.  <code>Future<\/code> also has some nice hook-ins with Java's concurrency utilities, but by the sound of it you don't need that.<\/p>\n\n<p>You'd use a <code>Supplier<\/code> like so:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class GlobalState {\n  public static final Supplier&lt;LazyData&gt; MY_DATA = Suppliers.memoize(\n    new Supplier&lt;LazyData&gt;() {\n      public LazyData get() {\n        // do whatever you need to construct your object, only gets executed once needed\n      }\n    });\n\n  ...\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/base/Suppliers.html#memoize%28com.google.common.base.Supplier%29\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Suppliers.memoize()<\/code><\/a> will cache the result of the first call to the underlying <code>Supplier<\/code> in a threadsafe way, so simply wrapping the <code>Supplier<\/code> you define with this call prevents duplicate processing.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 21193241,
            "question_id": 21192950,
            "last_edit_date": 1389983918
        }
    ],
